<Layout title="About — Trove Collections">
  <h1>About</h1>

  <p class="lede">
    Trove Collections is a small editorial shop run by my mom Micki and me. The
    rest of our curator circle — Auntie Kristen, Auntie Angie, our friends Cheryl
    Lynne and Tanya, and my dad — bring in items from their own travels. We are
    all in the same line of work. We see a lot of the world.
  </p>

  <h2>The rule</h2>
  <p>
    Every item on this site is one that someone in our circle has personally used.
    Not "looked at on a trip." Not "saw on Instagram." Used. The Tumi ottoman my
    mom has been pulling out of her travel bag for years. The bayu cream Auntie
    Angie keeps in her toiletry kit. The polenta pan the restaurant in Argentina
    sold to Auntie Kristen after she finished the dish they cooked her in it. The
    Korean toner my mom and I have been splitting between two countries.
  </p>
  <p>
    If a trend hits and none of us have actually tried it, it doesn't go here.
    That's the whole point.
  </p>

  <h2>Why we do this</h2>
  <p>
    Two reasons. The first is that we kept getting asked. Friends, our parents'
    friends, people who saw what we packed — "where did you get that?" came up
    often enough that writing it down made sense.
  </p>
  <p>
    The second is gift-shopping. Specifically: the kind of shopping where you're
    trying to find something for a college-age girl, or a grandmother who flies
    a lot, or a friend who already has everything. The internet is loud and the
    algorithms don't know your aunt. We do.
  </p>

  <h2>Who's in the circle</h2>
  <p>
    Mom (Micki) runs the regional collections — Tokyo, Korea, the Levant, the
    pieces from her own life on the road. <strong>Auntie Kristen</strong> handles
    Germany (through a longtime art-dealer friend), Brazil, Argentina, Panama,
    and Sydney. <strong>Auntie Angie</strong> contributes to East Asia and
    skincare. <strong>Cheryl Lynne</strong>, our fairy godmother, brings in
    Japan and the UK. <strong>Tanya</strong> lived in Italy and just vacationed
    there again — Italy is her territory. <strong>My dad</strong> flies
    international long-haul, so when he comes back with something useful — like
    the Brightline bag — it earns its way in. <strong>I'm Eris</strong>, my mom's
    daughter. I run "Eris's Picks" — beauty, small jewelry, the kinds of things
    that are easier to gift to someone who already has the big things.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    We make a small commission when you buy through our links. We never feature
    anything just because we could earn from it. <a href="/disclosure">Full disclosure here.</a>
  </p>
</Layout>

